No, they are not redundant.

That section of code is taking a hash chain, iterating over the nodes, and reassigning them to either a &quot;lo&quot; or &quot;hi&quot; chain.  The statements you identified are executed when that process has finished.  They are making sure that the last nodes in the &quot;lo&quot; and &quot;hi&quot; chains both have `null` as their `next`.  

If those statements weren&#39;t there, you could end up with some nodes appearing on *both* the &quot;lo&quot; and &quot;hi&quot; chains after the resize.  That would be *broken*.

This is the code section we are talking about from the Java 8 codebase

        else { // preserve order
            Node&lt;K,V&gt; loHead = null, loTail = null;
            Node&lt;K,V&gt; hiHead = null, hiTail = null;
